WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.410 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.410 --> 00:00:04.338 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.338 --> 00:00:05.784 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.784 --> 00:00:13.293 align:middle line:90%


00:00:13.293 --> 00:00:14.460 align:middle line:90%
PETER KEMPTHORNE: All right.

00:00:14.460 --> 00:00:16.520 align:middle line:90%
We'll get started.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:18.720 align:middle line:84%
What I wanted to do
today was to make

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:23.240 align:middle line:84%
sure we thoroughly cover
the theory and application

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:25.160 align:middle line:90%
of regression modeling.

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:30.360 align:middle line:84%
And so to begin,
there's a recap,

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:41.960 align:middle line:84%
which is the theory for, if
we have linear regression,

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:49.560 align:middle line:84%
and we have, in particular, a
normal linear regression model,

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:58.320 align:middle line:84%
then we have these properties
of beta hat being distributed

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:07.560 align:middle line:84%
as a multinormal random variable
with mean the true regression

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:14.520 align:middle line:84%
parameter and covariance matrix
given by the X transpose X

00:01:14.520 --> 00:01:17.920 align:middle line:84%
inverse multiplied
by sigma squared.

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:21.400 align:middle line:84%
And we also have
that epsilon hat

00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:24.280 align:middle line:90%
is a multinormal distribution--

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:29.000 align:middle line:84%
it's actually not of full rank,
but it's in n dimensions--

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.520 align:middle line:84%
with mean 0, a 0 vector,
and the covariance matrix

00:01:34.520 --> 00:01:40.680 align:middle line:84%
is sigma squared times the
identity minus the hat matrix.

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:46.560 align:middle line:84%
And with these
properties, we can

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:51.440 align:middle line:84%
show that they are independent
random variables, if we have

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:53.640 align:middle line:90%
the normal model assumption.

00:01:53.640 --> 00:02:01.940 align:middle line:84%
So these are independent if the
error vector is multinormal.

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:05.000 align:middle line:90%


00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:12.320 align:middle line:84%
And with that, we're able to
get an estimate of the error

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:18.680 align:middle line:84%
variance very easily
from the residual vector.

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:22.600 align:middle line:84%
The sum of squares of
the residual vector

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:26.760 align:middle line:84%
can be solved for having
expectation equal to n minus p

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:31.240 align:middle line:84%
sigma squared, and
that leads to dividing

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:33.760 align:middle line:84%
the sum of squared
residuals by n minus p

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:35.960 align:middle line:90%
to get an unbiased estimate.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:41.080 align:middle line:84%
Now, what's interesting
mathematically

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:47.360 align:middle line:84%
is that because this estimate
of the error variance

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:52.680 align:middle line:84%
depends on the residuals, which
are independent of beta hat,

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:57.720 align:middle line:84%
we can then use this information
to construct t-statistics

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:02.240 align:middle line:90%
for the least squares estimates.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:16.660 align:middle line:84%
So we have t-statistics for
the j-th component of the least

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:23.160 align:middle line:84%
squares estimate, so beta hat
sub j minus beta j divided

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:36.560 align:middle line:84%
by sigma hat Cjj where Cjj
is the j-th diagonal entry

00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:41.080 align:middle line:84%
of the variance--
inverse variance.

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:48.160 align:middle line:84%
And actually, the Cjj should be
equal to the square root of X

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:52.440 align:middle line:90%
transpose X inverse sub jj.

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:56.640 align:middle line:84%
So there's a square
root missing there.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:04:04.320 align:middle line:84%
And this distribution, under
the normal linear model, has--

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:09.520 align:middle line:84%
or this formula has
a t-distribution.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:14.560 align:middle line:84%
So this is distributed
as a t-distribution

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:19.440 align:middle line:84%
with n-minus-p degrees
of freedom, degrees

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:22.560 align:middle line:90%
of freedom equal to n minus p.

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:30.520 align:middle line:84%
And this is true if we
plug in the true beta j.

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:36.240 align:middle line:84%
So centering our least
squares estimate at beta j

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:38.520 align:middle line:90%
allows us to write that out.

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:44.840 align:middle line:84%
So if we look at
our beta hat value

00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:49.840 align:middle line:84%
and consider it around
the true beta j,

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:54.840 align:middle line:84%
we basically have a
t-distribution for the outcome.

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:58.280 align:middle line:84%
And why this becomes
very useful is

00:04:58.280 --> 00:05:02.320 align:middle line:84%
that if we want to test the
hypothesis that beta j is

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:11.200 align:middle line:84%
equal to 0, then
if this is 0, we

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:20.120 align:middle line:84%
can basically define
an interval around 0

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:26.700 align:middle line:84%
and consider rejecting
the null hypothesis

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:32.840 align:middle line:84%
if our t hat with beta j
equaling 0 in magnitude

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:35.600 align:middle line:84%
is greater than some
critical value--

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:38.040 align:middle line:90%
say, some constant C.

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:44.960 align:middle line:84%
And so this
t-statistic is commonly

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:50.080 align:middle line:84%
applied in judging
different regression models.

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:53.590 align:middle line:84%
Of particular interest
is whether factors can be

00:05:53.590 --> 00:05:56.750 align:middle line:90%
excluded from the regression.

00:05:56.750 --> 00:06:00.490 align:middle line:84%
So if a beta j
component is equal to 0,

00:06:00.490 --> 00:06:03.790 align:middle line:84%
that means we can just
exclude the variable.

00:06:03.790 --> 00:06:08.430 align:middle line:84%
Now, interestingly,
if we want to test

00:06:08.430 --> 00:06:14.550 align:middle line:84%
whether multiple beta
j's are equal to 0,

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:18.290 align:middle line:84%
a special case of
that is just to say,

00:06:18.290 --> 00:06:25.430 align:middle line:84%
let's assume that the first
k beta j's are nonzero.

00:06:25.430 --> 00:06:27.830 align:middle line:84%
We'll just assume
that that's true.

00:06:27.830 --> 00:06:33.310 align:middle line:84%
But let's test whether
the beta j's for j above k

00:06:33.310 --> 00:06:35.150 align:middle line:90%
are equal to 0.

00:06:35.150 --> 00:06:41.510 align:middle line:84%
And what we can do is
calculate residuals

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:46.510 align:middle line:90%
under the two hypotheses.

00:06:46.510 --> 00:06:53.750 align:middle line:84%
First, assuming that they're
all nonzero, we get an RSS 1.

00:06:53.750 --> 00:06:57.050 align:middle line:84%
But if we assume the
submodel is true,

00:06:57.050 --> 00:07:00.190 align:middle line:84%
we can get a second
set of residuals.

00:07:00.190 --> 00:07:07.550 align:middle line:84%
And because the
full model is more--

00:07:07.550 --> 00:07:12.230 align:middle line:84%
sort of, it minimizes the
sum of squares further, we

00:07:12.230 --> 00:07:16.710 align:middle line:84%
can look at the difference
in residual sum of squares,

00:07:16.710 --> 00:07:20.430 align:middle line:84%
normalize that by p
minus k, and compare

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:23.110 align:middle line:84%
that with the residual
sum of the squares

00:07:23.110 --> 00:07:26.090 align:middle line:84%
under the full model
divided by n minus p.

00:07:26.090 --> 00:07:30.710 align:middle line:84%
So this is an estimate of sigma
squared using the full model.

00:07:30.710 --> 00:07:32.910 align:middle line:84%
This numerator is
also an estimate

00:07:32.910 --> 00:07:39.390 align:middle line:84%
of sigma squared based on the
null hypothesis being true.

00:07:39.390 --> 00:07:43.750 align:middle line:84%
Now, what's interesting
to highlight

00:07:43.750 --> 00:07:53.350 align:middle line:84%
is that the F-test when k, the
number of nonzero coefficients,

00:07:53.350 --> 00:07:57.630 align:middle line:84%
is p minus 1, then this
F-test corresponds to testing

00:07:57.630 --> 00:08:02.030 align:middle line:84%
whether the p-th
beta j is equal to 0.

00:08:02.030 --> 00:08:10.550 align:middle line:84%
And so it turns out that
if we have t hat p--

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:16.070 align:middle line:84%
sorry-- t hat,
yeah, p, of beta--

00:08:16.070 --> 00:08:20.950 align:middle line:84%
of the true beta,
the beta with beta p

00:08:20.950 --> 00:08:26.830 align:middle line:84%
equal to 0- this
squared is actually

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:28.916 align:middle line:90%
equal to this F-statistic.

00:08:28.916 --> 00:08:33.817 align:middle line:90%


00:08:33.817 --> 00:08:35.630 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS] I'm just going to--

00:08:35.630 --> 00:08:40.150 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHS] there's a huge
rumbling in the room right now.

00:08:40.150 --> 00:08:43.950 align:middle line:84%
And if anyone
finds out that it's

00:08:43.950 --> 00:08:46.130 align:middle line:84%
something serious we
should be thinking about,

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:50.910 align:middle line:84%
please let me know, [LAUGHS]
or let the whole class know.

00:08:50.910 --> 00:08:55.230 align:middle line:84%
It sort of sounds like an
earthquake, which I experienced

00:08:55.230 --> 00:08:57.535 align:middle line:90%
when I was at UC Berkeley.

00:08:57.535 --> 00:09:01.150 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHS] Anyway, all
right, well, we'll

00:09:01.150 --> 00:09:04.030 align:middle line:84%
continue, unless I get
warnings from you all.

00:09:04.030 --> 00:09:07.710 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, it turns out that this
t-squared statistic is actually

00:09:07.710 --> 00:09:10.610 align:middle line:84%
equal to the F-test
formalized here.

00:09:10.610 --> 00:09:13.850 align:middle line:90%
So F-tests are very useful.

00:09:13.850 --> 00:09:17.830 align:middle line:84%
In special cases, they're
equivalent to the square

00:09:17.830 --> 00:09:21.870 align:middle line:90%
of a t-test statistic.

00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:28.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's see, with the
notes from last time,

00:09:28.910 --> 00:09:30.950 align:middle line:90%
we went through these.

00:09:30.950 --> 00:09:39.950 align:middle line:84%
We highlighted how, with
generalized least squares--

00:09:39.950 --> 00:09:43.620 align:middle line:84%
this is another key takeaway
in regression modeling.

00:09:43.620 --> 00:09:46.430 align:middle line:90%


00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:53.710 align:middle line:84%
So, so generalized
least squares,

00:09:53.710 --> 00:09:56.350 align:middle line:84%
with generalized
least squares, we

00:09:56.350 --> 00:10:02.510 align:middle line:84%
have an error
vector, which is not

00:10:02.510 --> 00:10:07.670 align:middle line:84%
a diagonal identity
times sigma squared,

00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:17.030 align:middle line:84%
but it's some base matrix sigma
times little sigma squared.

00:10:17.030 --> 00:10:20.750 align:middle line:84%
And with this setup,
we can actually

00:10:20.750 --> 00:10:27.550 align:middle line:84%
transform this regression
model into one which satisfies

00:10:27.550 --> 00:10:30.190 align:middle line:90%
our Gauss-Markov assumptions.

00:10:30.190 --> 00:10:36.950 align:middle line:84%
And then, so with x star and y
star being the model equation

00:10:36.950 --> 00:10:44.150 align:middle line:84%
multiplied by the inverse
square root of sigma, then

00:10:44.150 --> 00:10:47.710 align:middle line:84%
this model satisfies the
Gauss-Markov assumptions,

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:53.630 align:middle line:84%
zero-mean constant variance,
and so this estimator,

00:10:53.630 --> 00:10:56.830 align:middle line:84%
with the X stars and Y
stars but the same beta,

00:10:56.830 --> 00:11:00.450 align:middle line:84%
gives us our best
estimate of the beta hat--

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:04.390 align:middle line:84%
best in terms of minimum
being unbiased and having

00:11:04.390 --> 00:11:07.350 align:middle line:90%
smallest variance.

00:11:07.350 --> 00:11:08.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:08.190 --> 00:11:16.910 align:middle line:84%
Well, a next important
aspect of regression modeling

00:11:16.910 --> 00:11:28.270 align:middle line:84%
is looking at Maximum
Likelihood Estimation, MLE.

00:11:28.270 --> 00:11:32.710 align:middle line:84%
And for maximum
likelihood estimation,

00:11:32.710 --> 00:11:40.310 align:middle line:84%
we use the probability model
of the regression-- which,

00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:46.150 align:middle line:84%
in this case, is normal linear
regression models, so if we

00:11:46.150 --> 00:11:52.070 align:middle line:90%
have normal epsilon vector.

00:11:52.070 --> 00:11:58.790 align:middle line:84%
Then we compute the
density of our data Y,

00:11:58.790 --> 00:12:02.870 align:middle line:84%
given the explanatory
variables in X,

00:12:02.870 --> 00:12:09.310 align:middle line:84%
and the beta, regression
parameter beta.

00:12:09.310 --> 00:12:11.110 align:middle line:90%
That should be a beta there.

00:12:11.110 --> 00:12:16.870 align:middle line:84%
And we simply identify
those parameter values

00:12:16.870 --> 00:12:20.950 align:middle line:90%
that maximize this probability.

00:12:20.950 --> 00:12:22.430 align:middle line:84%
So we're looking
at the parameter

00:12:22.430 --> 00:12:28.350 align:middle line:84%
values that make the data
we observed the most likely.

00:12:28.350 --> 00:12:33.310 align:middle line:84%
And intuitively, that's
maybe a reasonable thing.

00:12:33.310 --> 00:12:37.810 align:middle line:84%
If you take Mathematical
Statistics next term,

00:12:37.810 --> 00:12:40.910 align:middle line:84%
you'll learn that
that, in fact, is

00:12:40.910 --> 00:12:48.190 align:middle line:84%
an optimal estimator, in terms
of having smallest variance

00:12:48.190 --> 00:12:49.350 align:middle line:90%
in large samples.

00:12:49.350 --> 00:12:54.630 align:middle line:84%
As the sample size, the
number of cases n increases,

00:12:54.630 --> 00:12:57.910 align:middle line:84%
this will lead to
the best estimator.

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:02.070 align:middle line:90%
And this MLE for the best--

00:13:02.070 --> 00:13:04.990 align:middle line:84%
or the best estimator
being the MLE

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:09.230 align:middle line:84%
will be true for different
distributions as well.

00:13:09.230 --> 00:13:14.750 align:middle line:84%
We're going to show what it is
for the Gaussian distribution.

00:13:14.750 --> 00:13:19.590 align:middle line:84%
And what we can
see on this slide

00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:23.310 align:middle line:84%
is that the log
of the likelihood

00:13:23.310 --> 00:13:27.510 align:middle line:84%
is the log of this
density on the top line.

00:13:27.510 --> 00:13:34.750 align:middle line:84%
It can be equal to minus n over
2 log sigma squared minus 1/2

00:13:34.750 --> 00:13:39.310 align:middle line:84%
sigma squared q of beta, where
q of beta is our least squares

00:13:39.310 --> 00:13:40.790 align:middle line:90%
criterion.

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:45.150 align:middle line:84%
So maximum likelihood estimation
for normal linear regression

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:50.230 align:middle line:90%
models can proceed in two steps.

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:57.950 align:middle line:84%
First, we can see that the beta
regression coefficient enters in

00:13:57.950 --> 00:14:01.630 align:middle line:84%
only through a
factor of Q of beta.

00:14:01.630 --> 00:14:08.270 align:middle line:84%
So minimizing Q of beta
gives us the MLE for beta.

00:14:08.270 --> 00:14:11.710 align:middle line:84%
And then once we have
the MLE for beta,

00:14:11.710 --> 00:14:17.630 align:middle line:84%
we can plug that in to the
likelihood, the log likelihood--

00:14:17.630 --> 00:14:22.990 align:middle line:84%
or the likelihood, for
varying sigma squared.

00:14:22.990 --> 00:14:27.630 align:middle line:84%
And when we do this,
we actually can just

00:14:27.630 --> 00:14:33.590 align:middle line:84%
maximize this sort
of partial likelihood

00:14:33.590 --> 00:14:37.030 align:middle line:90%
with beta fixed at beta hat.

00:14:37.030 --> 00:14:39.230 align:middle line:84%
Maximize that over
sigma squared,

00:14:39.230 --> 00:14:43.310 align:middle line:84%
and that turns out to be a very
easy computation, calculating

00:14:43.310 --> 00:14:49.670 align:middle line:84%
the first-order equation
for the log likelihood.

00:14:49.670 --> 00:14:53.110 align:middle line:84%
And we get the maximum
likelihood estimate is simply

00:14:53.110 --> 00:14:57.750 align:middle line:84%
the sum of squared
residuals divided by n.

00:14:57.750 --> 00:15:02.470 align:middle line:84%
Now, with maximum
likelihood, in this case,

00:15:02.470 --> 00:15:07.190 align:middle line:84%
we have, actually, a biased
estimate of the error variance.

00:15:07.190 --> 00:15:14.270 align:middle line:84%
And it's important just to
note that that's the case.

00:15:14.270 --> 00:15:16.110 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:15:16.110 --> 00:15:20.710 align:middle line:84%
Well, what's interesting
to generalize

00:15:20.710 --> 00:15:27.990 align:middle line:84%
is to find estimators,
which minimize

00:15:27.990 --> 00:15:31.870 align:middle line:84%
a Q function, which may be
different from least squares--

00:15:31.870 --> 00:15:33.510 align:middle line:90%
or sum of squares.

00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:38.340 align:middle line:84%
And so we can
consider a Q function

00:15:38.340 --> 00:15:47.780 align:middle line:84%
which minimizes the sum of a
function h evaluated at case i.

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:50.740 align:middle line:90%
So let's see here.

00:15:50.740 --> 00:15:54.740 align:middle line:90%
Let's pull this down.

00:15:54.740 --> 00:16:09.820 align:middle line:84%
So, so with generalized
M-estimators,

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:14.300 align:middle line:84%
we think of Q of beta
being the sum 1 to n

00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:22.230 align:middle line:84%
of h of y i, the x i beta,
and sigma squared, I guess.

00:16:22.230 --> 00:16:24.740 align:middle line:90%


00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:27.860 align:middle line:84%
And the choice of h,
well, if we choose h

00:16:27.860 --> 00:16:35.660 align:middle line:84%
to just be the square of the
linear estimate of y given x i,

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:37.500 align:middle line:90%
that's least squares.

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:42.700 align:middle line:84%
There's no reason, in principle,
why we should use squares.

00:16:42.700 --> 00:16:47.460 align:middle line:84%
We could use absolute
deviations and sum those.

00:16:47.460 --> 00:16:53.660 align:middle line:84%
And if we wanted maximum
likelihood estimates,

00:16:53.660 --> 00:16:58.860 align:middle line:84%
we could choose h to be
minus the log of the density.

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:04.780 align:middle line:84%
And there are robust
estimators in statistics.

00:17:04.780 --> 00:17:13.540 align:middle line:84%
And these robust estimators
consider variations, basically,

00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:20.500 align:middle line:84%
of least squares and
mean absolute deviations

00:17:20.500 --> 00:17:25.339 align:middle line:84%
as special cases, that yield
estimators that are robust.

00:17:25.339 --> 00:17:30.060 align:middle line:84%
Now, what's, to me, very
interesting is that if we were

00:17:30.060 --> 00:17:36.060 align:middle line:84%
to know what the density
is of the errors,

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:40.580 align:middle line:84%
then maximum likelihood
estimation would say use that.

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:44.020 align:middle line:84%
When we don't know
the distribution,

00:17:44.020 --> 00:17:50.020 align:middle line:84%
then these others may be
very useful as alternatives.

00:17:50.020 --> 00:17:55.820 align:middle line:84%
And robust estimators
were originally

00:17:55.820 --> 00:18:01.180 align:middle line:84%
proposed for models where we
may have a normal distribution

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:04.180 align:middle line:84%
most of the time, but
some contamination

00:18:04.180 --> 00:18:11.660 align:middle line:84%
distribution with large errors
a small percentage of the time.

00:18:11.660 --> 00:18:15.820 align:middle line:84%
Now, and another
interesting example

00:18:15.820 --> 00:18:23.020 align:middle line:84%
of this generalized M-estimator
is the quantile estimator,

00:18:23.020 --> 00:18:28.220 align:middle line:84%
where we consider sort of
mean absolute deviation,

00:18:28.220 --> 00:18:37.020 align:middle line:84%
but we scale that for positive
residuals by a factor tau.

00:18:37.020 --> 00:18:41.720 align:middle line:84%
And for negative
values of the residual,

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:46.200 align:middle line:84%
we scale the absolute
deviation by 1 minus tau.

00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:50.060 align:middle line:90%


00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:55.820 align:middle line:84%
This h function
basically is equivalent

00:18:55.820 --> 00:19:05.820 align:middle line:84%
to the mean absolute deviation
when tau is equal to 0.5.

00:19:05.820 --> 00:19:10.660 align:middle line:90%
But when tau is--

00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:14.300 align:middle line:90%
if we have h--

00:19:14.300 --> 00:19:17.140 align:middle line:90%
let's see.

00:19:17.140 --> 00:19:25.460 align:middle line:84%
So h of y, x, when this is
equal to tau y i minus x i

00:19:25.460 --> 00:19:34.540 align:middle line:90%
beta when this is positive.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:38.840 align:middle line:84%
And it's equal to 1
minus tau when this is--

00:19:38.840 --> 00:19:41.620 align:middle line:90%


00:19:41.620 --> 00:19:48.820 align:middle line:84%
actually, it's equal to minus
this when this is less than 0.

00:19:48.820 --> 00:19:54.400 align:middle line:84%
Then, for example, when
tau is equal to 0.9,

00:19:54.400 --> 00:20:01.740 align:middle line:84%
this turns out to be a quantile
estimate that is working

00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:07.380 align:middle line:84%
to estimate the 90th
percentile of outcomes.

00:20:07.380 --> 00:20:16.780 align:middle line:84%
So when we have a regression
model and we are sort of just--

00:20:16.780 --> 00:20:20.420 align:middle line:84%
if we have a bunch
of points, and we

00:20:20.420 --> 00:20:23.000 align:middle line:84%
consider a linear
regression model,

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:28.980 align:middle line:90%
this would be y equal to--

00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:32.740 align:middle line:84%
or y hat equal to sort of
the mean absolute deviation

00:20:32.740 --> 00:20:41.420 align:middle line:84%
estimate, we actually can get
estimates of the 90th percentile

00:20:41.420 --> 00:20:45.740 align:middle line:84%
of outcomes of the
regression model.

00:20:45.740 --> 00:20:53.060 align:middle line:84%
Now, what's interesting
mathematically

00:20:53.060 --> 00:20:59.660 align:middle line:84%
is, How would one calculate sort
of the mean absolute deviation

00:20:59.660 --> 00:21:03.300 align:middle line:84%
estimate, or this
quantile estimator?

00:21:03.300 --> 00:21:11.220 align:middle line:84%
Well, we would want to minimize
the sum of these h functions.

00:21:11.220 --> 00:21:15.706 align:middle line:84%
And these h functions
actually are convex.

00:21:15.706 --> 00:21:18.220 align:middle line:90%


00:21:18.220 --> 00:21:22.700 align:middle line:84%
So as James Sheppard said, this
is, like, a bowl-shaped problem.

00:21:22.700 --> 00:21:25.580 align:middle line:84%
But it's a bowl with
sort of square--

00:21:25.580 --> 00:21:29.680 align:middle line:84%
or with straight
edges around it.

00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:36.540 align:middle line:84%
And so if we take this
Q function with this h,

00:21:36.540 --> 00:21:42.460 align:middle line:84%
we can't minimize it by solving
the first-order equations.

00:21:42.460 --> 00:21:50.140 align:middle line:84%
So if we have Q equal to the sum
1 to n of h of the arguments,

00:21:50.140 --> 00:21:51.650 align:middle line:90%
we can't solve this--

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:55.140 align:middle line:90%


00:21:55.140 --> 00:21:58.340 align:middle line:84%
we can't solve for
this equaling 0.

00:21:58.340 --> 00:22:04.380 align:middle line:84%
But we can solve for what the
derivative is at any guesses,

00:22:04.380 --> 00:22:12.580 align:middle line:84%
and we can move our guess to a
lower value of the Q function

00:22:12.580 --> 00:22:13.160 align:middle line:90%
with that.

00:22:13.160 --> 00:22:15.780 align:middle line:84%
And that's, in
fact, how we learn

00:22:15.780 --> 00:22:23.060 align:middle line:84%
that the median of
a sample is the best

00:22:23.060 --> 00:22:26.580 align:middle line:84%
estimate of the
center of the data

00:22:26.580 --> 00:22:31.220 align:middle line:84%
if we consider mean
absolute deviations.

00:22:31.220 --> 00:22:33.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:40.980 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's consider another
extension of regression.

00:22:40.980 --> 00:22:46.060 align:middle line:84%
It's famous enough to have its
own name, ridge regression.

00:22:46.060 --> 00:22:52.860 align:middle line:84%
And so with ridge regression,
we are estimating the regression

00:22:52.860 --> 00:23:00.300 align:middle line:90%
parameters where we have--

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:03.340 align:middle line:84%
basically, it's sort
of least squares

00:23:03.340 --> 00:23:10.700 align:middle line:84%
plus a penalty,
for our criterion.

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:18.460 align:middle line:84%
So the left argument
of this expression

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:21.780 align:middle line:84%
is simply the sum of
squared residuals,

00:23:21.780 --> 00:23:24.980 align:middle line:84%
but then we're adding
to that a penalty

00:23:24.980 --> 00:23:30.140 align:middle line:84%
depending upon the squared
length of the beta vector.

00:23:30.140 --> 00:23:40.800 align:middle line:84%
And so in order for this to
be a reasonable thing to do,

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:43.980 align:middle line:90%
we actually need to--

00:23:43.980 --> 00:23:47.700 align:middle line:84%
or, we don't need
to, but it's useful,

00:23:47.700 --> 00:23:55.060 align:middle line:84%
to consider standardizing
our independent variables x,

00:23:55.060 --> 00:24:03.340 align:middle line:84%
making them have mean
0, and also centering y,

00:24:03.340 --> 00:24:07.380 align:middle line:84%
and then consider
the regression where

00:24:07.380 --> 00:24:15.860 align:middle line:84%
we rescale the columns of the
predictor matrix as centered

00:24:15.860 --> 00:24:20.900 align:middle line:84%
with the inverse of the
covariance matrix between those.

00:24:20.900 --> 00:24:30.060 align:middle line:84%
So in this formulation,
this is the statement

00:24:30.060 --> 00:24:35.880 align:middle line:84%
of how the ridge regression
parameter estimate is specified.

00:24:35.880 --> 00:24:41.660 align:middle line:84%
Now, the centering of
the independent variables

00:24:41.660 --> 00:24:45.260 align:middle line:84%
and scaling them to
have unit variance

00:24:45.260 --> 00:24:49.140 align:middle line:84%
is important because
it places all

00:24:49.140 --> 00:24:52.020 align:middle line:84%
of the variables, all of
the predictor variables,

00:24:52.020 --> 00:24:54.700 align:middle line:90%
on an equal footing.

00:24:54.700 --> 00:25:02.460 align:middle line:84%
If we are looking at the sum
of squared beta j's, then

00:25:02.460 --> 00:25:04.700 align:middle line:84%
if we just use
different units, we

00:25:04.700 --> 00:25:11.660 align:middle line:84%
could make any j beta, beta
j, as large as we want.

00:25:11.660 --> 00:25:16.500 align:middle line:84%
But with this
standardization, we basically

00:25:16.500 --> 00:25:21.100 align:middle line:84%
eliminate that aspect,
so there's no dependence

00:25:21.100 --> 00:25:24.540 align:middle line:90%
on the original units of X.

00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:27.820 align:middle line:90%
And let's see.

00:25:27.820 --> 00:25:30.540 align:middle line:84%
With this ridge
regression, the notes

00:25:30.540 --> 00:25:34.660 align:middle line:90%
go through how we compute these.

00:25:34.660 --> 00:25:42.380 align:middle line:84%
I want to highlight, though,
how this ridge regression is

00:25:42.380 --> 00:25:46.860 align:middle line:84%
actually related to
Bayesian models, where

00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:52.380 align:middle line:84%
we would assume a prior
distribution on our regression

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:54.020 align:middle line:90%
parameters.

00:25:54.020 --> 00:26:06.100 align:middle line:84%
And so the-- if we consider
a Bayes prior on beta,

00:26:06.100 --> 00:26:17.010 align:middle line:84%
and that Bayes prior is
basically multinormal in p

00:26:17.010 --> 00:26:24.130 align:middle line:84%
dimensions, with a
mean vector of 0,

00:26:24.130 --> 00:26:29.520 align:middle line:84%
and a covariance
matrix that is--

00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:32.090 align:middle line:90%


00:26:32.090 --> 00:26:35.330 align:middle line:84%
let's see, I'll call
it omega, and omega

00:26:35.330 --> 00:26:42.770 align:middle line:84%
is proportional to the identity
matrix in p dimensions.

00:26:42.770 --> 00:26:50.210 align:middle line:84%
Then what we've done is
we have a criterion that

00:26:50.210 --> 00:26:58.930 align:middle line:84%
corresponds to the exponential
part of the log likelihood for--

00:26:58.930 --> 00:27:02.850 align:middle line:84%
plus the log likelihood
of the prior density.

00:27:02.850 --> 00:27:09.690 align:middle line:84%
So this ridge regression
is interpretable as putting

00:27:09.690 --> 00:27:17.370 align:middle line:84%
a prior distribution on the
betas that have this form,

00:27:17.370 --> 00:27:21.730 align:middle line:84%
mean 0, and covariance
proportional

00:27:21.730 --> 00:27:24.050 align:middle line:90%
to the identity matrix.

00:27:24.050 --> 00:27:26.890 align:middle line:84%
And what that
suggests a priori is

00:27:26.890 --> 00:27:32.530 align:middle line:84%
that any direction in
that p-dimensional space

00:27:32.530 --> 00:27:37.570 align:middle line:84%
is equally likely as any
other for characterizing

00:27:37.570 --> 00:27:40.330 align:middle line:90%
the regression parameters.

00:27:40.330 --> 00:27:44.810 align:middle line:84%
And this beta hat, which
minimizes this argument,

00:27:44.810 --> 00:27:49.850 align:middle line:84%
ends up being the mode of
the posterior distribution.

00:27:49.850 --> 00:27:55.770 align:middle line:84%
So that's a neat
connection to be aware of.

00:27:55.770 --> 00:28:00.370 align:middle line:84%
The notes here go through,
with ridge regression,

00:28:00.370 --> 00:28:04.370 align:middle line:90%
how we compute them.

00:28:04.370 --> 00:28:09.850 align:middle line:84%
The minimization basically
leads to formulas

00:28:09.850 --> 00:28:13.090 align:middle line:84%
for the ridge regression
estimate that look almost

00:28:13.090 --> 00:28:15.050 align:middle line:84%
like least squares,
except we have

00:28:15.050 --> 00:28:18.410 align:middle line:84%
this additional factor,
lambda times the identity,

00:28:18.410 --> 00:28:22.770 align:middle line:84%
inside that braces, before
we take the inverse.

00:28:22.770 --> 00:28:29.690 align:middle line:84%
And with ridge regression, we
can look at the singular value

00:28:29.690 --> 00:28:34.930 align:middle line:84%
decomposition of our
independent variables

00:28:34.930 --> 00:28:40.650 align:middle line:84%
that have been centered
and standardized.

00:28:40.650 --> 00:28:48.530 align:middle line:84%
And when we do that we basically
have this final formula

00:28:48.530 --> 00:28:53.890 align:middle line:90%
for the ridge regression.

00:28:53.890 --> 00:29:04.050 align:middle line:84%
And we end up basically having
the fitted values y hat just

00:29:04.050 --> 00:29:12.050 align:middle line:84%
being equal to a sum
of factors times cj uj,

00:29:12.050 --> 00:29:20.430 align:middle line:84%
where these factors
are 1 when lambda is 0.

00:29:20.430 --> 00:29:25.010 align:middle line:84%
So when lambda is 0, ridge
is equal to least squares.

00:29:25.010 --> 00:29:29.650 align:middle line:84%
And so the least squares
fitted values are given here.

00:29:29.650 --> 00:29:35.290 align:middle line:84%
But with ridge regression,
we have shrinkage.

00:29:35.290 --> 00:29:39.010 align:middle line:84%
And what's curious
is that there's

00:29:39.010 --> 00:29:46.210 align:middle line:84%
less shrinkage for the larger
squared singular values,

00:29:46.210 --> 00:29:50.490 align:middle line:84%
and there's more shrinkage
for the smaller ones.

00:29:50.490 --> 00:29:53.690 align:middle line:84%
So if we think of the
independent variables,

00:29:53.690 --> 00:29:58.970 align:middle line:84%
or predictor variables,
being in p-dimensional space,

00:29:58.970 --> 00:30:05.850 align:middle line:84%
then ridge regression
will not shrink

00:30:05.850 --> 00:30:09.370 align:middle line:84%
much those regression
coefficients

00:30:09.370 --> 00:30:15.210 align:middle line:84%
that correspond to
regressor variables

00:30:15.210 --> 00:30:19.890 align:middle line:84%
that are along sort of the
first principal component axis.

00:30:19.890 --> 00:30:24.210 align:middle line:84%
And there's much more
shrinkage in those dimensions

00:30:24.210 --> 00:30:27.150 align:middle line:84%
where there's very
little variation.

00:30:27.150 --> 00:30:33.050 align:middle line:84%
So these are actually connected
to principal components

00:30:33.050 --> 00:30:35.910 align:middle line:84%
variables, which
is actually covered

00:30:35.910 --> 00:30:40.930 align:middle line:90%
sort of in the next section.

00:30:40.930 --> 00:30:43.850 align:middle line:90%
So, yeah, it was--

00:30:43.850 --> 00:30:46.850 align:middle line:84%
we introduced ridge regression
using the singular value

00:30:46.850 --> 00:30:53.650 align:middle line:84%
decomposition of X. But we can
motivate principal components

00:30:53.650 --> 00:30:58.890 align:middle line:84%
regression using the same
singular value decomposition.

00:30:58.890 --> 00:31:05.810 align:middle line:84%
So with our data
predictor matrix X,

00:31:05.810 --> 00:31:09.170 align:middle line:84%
we consider the sample
covariance matrix

00:31:09.170 --> 00:31:12.690 align:middle line:90%
of those row vectors.

00:31:12.690 --> 00:31:18.370 align:middle line:84%
And we can compute the
eigenvalue eigenvector

00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:21.370 align:middle line:90%
decomposition of that.

00:31:21.370 --> 00:31:25.010 align:middle line:84%
And with these
eigenvectors, which

00:31:25.010 --> 00:31:34.650 align:middle line:84%
are normalized to have length 1,
we simply multiply our matrix X

00:31:34.650 --> 00:31:39.570 align:middle line:84%
by the j-th eigenvector, and we
get our j-th principal component

00:31:39.570 --> 00:31:41.810 align:middle line:90%
variable.

00:31:41.810 --> 00:31:46.250 align:middle line:84%
So this is familiar to us
in, terms of how principal

00:31:46.250 --> 00:31:50.690 align:middle line:84%
components sort of
computations work.

00:31:50.690 --> 00:31:57.050 align:middle line:84%
And with principal
components regression,

00:31:57.050 --> 00:32:02.070 align:middle line:84%
one has principal
component variables

00:32:02.070 --> 00:32:05.890 align:middle line:84%
which are orthogonal
to each other,

00:32:05.890 --> 00:32:13.890 align:middle line:84%
and so the computation of their
coefficients is very simple.

00:32:13.890 --> 00:32:16.970 align:middle line:84%
We can calculate
them separately,

00:32:16.970 --> 00:32:20.330 align:middle line:84%
and we can consider
using maybe just

00:32:20.330 --> 00:32:25.930 align:middle line:84%
the first m principal component
variables in our regression.

00:32:25.930 --> 00:32:33.570 align:middle line:84%
And so if we do this, we
can see some easy formulas

00:32:33.570 --> 00:32:38.050 align:middle line:90%
for the estimates.

00:32:38.050 --> 00:32:45.170 align:middle line:84%
Ultimately, we get
fitted values of y,

00:32:45.170 --> 00:32:46.830 align:middle line:84%
from principal
components regression,

00:32:46.830 --> 00:32:53.290 align:middle line:84%
which are a projection of the
Y vector onto the space spanned

00:32:53.290 --> 00:32:54.020 align:middle line:90%
by the first--

00:32:54.020 --> 00:32:56.610 align:middle line:90%


00:32:56.610 --> 00:33:03.290 align:middle line:84%
in this case, the first m
principal component directions.

00:33:03.290 --> 00:33:09.390 align:middle line:84%
And what's curious is just
how these three methods--

00:33:09.390 --> 00:33:11.410 align:middle line:84%
least squares, ridge,
and principal components

00:33:11.410 --> 00:33:12.770 align:middle line:90%
regression--

00:33:12.770 --> 00:33:19.010 align:middle line:84%
are estimating the response
variable, or dependent variable,

00:33:19.010 --> 00:33:23.370 align:middle line:84%
using essentially the
same fundamental pieces,

00:33:23.370 --> 00:33:30.970 align:middle line:84%
the cj and uj's, but
are either skipping

00:33:30.970 --> 00:33:34.570 align:middle line:84%
the last p minus m for
principal components,

00:33:34.570 --> 00:33:37.290 align:middle line:84%
shrinking those
based on the size

00:33:37.290 --> 00:33:42.430 align:middle line:84%
of the eigenvalues for
ridge, or using all of them.

00:33:42.430 --> 00:33:45.850 align:middle line:90%


00:33:45.850 --> 00:33:52.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, as you might
expect, researchers

00:33:52.410 --> 00:33:58.650 align:middle line:84%
have extended estimation
methods beyond these.

00:33:58.650 --> 00:34:04.370 align:middle line:84%
The LASSO regression model,
or regression estimate,

00:34:04.370 --> 00:34:10.770 align:middle line:84%
is one where, instead
of having the penalty be

00:34:10.770 --> 00:34:16.650 align:middle line:84%
the sum of squared beta j's
or the length of the beta j,

00:34:16.650 --> 00:34:19.979 align:middle line:84%
it's the sum of the
absolute values.

00:34:19.979 --> 00:34:22.690 align:middle line:90%


00:34:22.690 --> 00:34:28.449 align:middle line:84%
And this penalty is a
really interesting one.

00:34:28.449 --> 00:34:29.989 align:middle line:90%
And some of-- let's see.

00:34:29.989 --> 00:34:34.750 align:middle line:84%
I'm sure some people here have
perhaps used lasso regression.

00:34:34.750 --> 00:34:38.370 align:middle line:84%
Has anyone here used
lasso regression?

00:34:38.370 --> 00:34:39.650 align:middle line:90%
Nobody?

00:34:39.650 --> 00:34:41.409 align:middle line:90%
That's fine.

00:34:41.409 --> 00:34:45.489 align:middle line:84%
That means this isn't sort
of repeat information.

00:34:45.489 --> 00:34:47.980 align:middle line:90%
But it turns out that--

00:34:47.980 --> 00:34:50.850 align:middle line:90%


00:34:50.850 --> 00:34:53.330 align:middle line:90%
well, let me just draw this.

00:34:53.330 --> 00:34:58.250 align:middle line:84%
Suppose we have beta
1 versus beta 2,

00:34:58.250 --> 00:35:03.142 align:middle line:90%
and we're considering penalties.

00:35:03.142 --> 00:35:06.050 align:middle line:90%


00:35:06.050 --> 00:35:10.570 align:middle line:84%
So the sum of the beta j
squareds equal to a constant,

00:35:10.570 --> 00:35:12.600 align:middle line:84%
this is the sort
of ridge penalty.

00:35:12.600 --> 00:35:17.490 align:middle line:90%


00:35:17.490 --> 00:35:28.190 align:middle line:84%
So, so if we have a beta
hat, say, a beta hat here,

00:35:28.190 --> 00:35:31.610 align:middle line:84%
a point that we
observe, it basically

00:35:31.610 --> 00:35:34.850 align:middle line:90%
is sort of shrunk towards zero.

00:35:34.850 --> 00:35:39.970 align:middle line:84%
Or we have beta hat,
and the beta-hat ridge

00:35:39.970 --> 00:35:49.090 align:middle line:84%
will be shrunk towards this
prior mean some amount.

00:35:49.090 --> 00:35:57.050 align:middle line:84%
With the lasso penalty,
we have the sum

00:35:57.050 --> 00:36:02.650 align:middle line:84%
of the magnitudes of the beta
j's is equal to a constant.

00:36:02.650 --> 00:36:10.450 align:middle line:84%
Then we basically
have diamonds where,

00:36:10.450 --> 00:36:14.090 align:middle line:84%
along each of these
diamond edges,

00:36:14.090 --> 00:36:17.650 align:middle line:84%
the penalty is the
same magnitude.

00:36:17.650 --> 00:36:22.370 align:middle line:84%
And so with lasso
regression, we basically

00:36:22.370 --> 00:36:31.890 align:middle line:84%
consider finding an estimate
that minimizes the least squares

00:36:31.890 --> 00:36:37.340 align:middle line:84%
but also is constrained
to have sort

00:36:37.340 --> 00:36:42.510 align:middle line:84%
of sum of absolute
magnitudes that's smaller.

00:36:42.510 --> 00:36:48.930 align:middle line:84%
And so this kind of
penalty ends up actually

00:36:48.930 --> 00:36:54.810 align:middle line:84%
leading to shrinkage,
which tends

00:36:54.810 --> 00:37:01.760 align:middle line:84%
to concentrate at the vertices
of this penalty function.

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:05.000 align:middle line:84%
So what we end up
getting, often,

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:10.580 align:middle line:84%
is a lasso estimate that
has some null parameters,

00:37:10.580 --> 00:37:12.060 align:middle line:90%
zero-value parameters.

00:37:12.060 --> 00:37:16.840 align:middle line:84%
So it's a way of excluding
variables from the regression,

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:18.710 align:middle line:90%
depending on what lambda is.

00:37:18.710 --> 00:37:22.040 align:middle line:90%


00:37:22.040 --> 00:37:24.120 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:25.340 align:middle line:90%
Well, let's see.

00:37:25.340 --> 00:37:32.840 align:middle line:84%
There's this ETF case
study that I posted which--

00:37:32.840 --> 00:37:35.640 align:middle line:90%


00:37:35.640 --> 00:37:40.000 align:middle line:84%
and it's sort of a long
document to sift through,

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:44.400 align:middle line:84%
but I guess what's
important is just

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:46.480 align:middle line:84%
to look at the table
of contents to see

00:37:46.480 --> 00:37:49.360 align:middle line:84%
what's of interest
to check out in this.

00:37:49.360 --> 00:37:54.040 align:middle line:84%
And what I set up
as a problem was

00:37:54.040 --> 00:38:02.680 align:middle line:84%
to consider collecting prices
on exchange-traded funds

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:07.080 align:middle line:84%
that correspond to different
sectors in the US market.

00:38:07.080 --> 00:38:12.720 align:middle line:84%
And so in the US market,
there are about 10 sectors--

00:38:12.720 --> 00:38:16.060 align:middle line:84%
consumer staples,
energy, financials,

00:38:16.060 --> 00:38:17.640 align:middle line:90%
health, and so forth.

00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:23.320 align:middle line:84%
And then there are also
exchange-traded funds

00:38:23.320 --> 00:38:29.280 align:middle line:84%
that correspond to market
indexes, like the S&P 500

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:35.440 align:middle line:84%
or the Dow Jones Industrial
or the NASDAQ market.

00:38:35.440 --> 00:38:45.960 align:middle line:84%
And I consider regressing a
sector ETF on the index ETFs.

00:38:45.960 --> 00:38:54.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, why would we be interested
in regressing a sector index

00:38:54.560 --> 00:39:03.308 align:middle line:90%
on these market-index ETFs?

00:39:03.308 --> 00:39:04.754 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:04.754 --> 00:39:12.000 align:middle line:90%


00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:16.160 align:middle line:84%
PETER KEMPTHORNE: Well, let
me just go through here.

00:39:16.160 --> 00:39:16.852 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:16.852 --> 00:39:20.640 align:middle line:84%
Or, this document goes
through, listing the symbols

00:39:20.640 --> 00:39:32.760 align:middle line:84%
for all of these different ETFs,
plotting them, and actually

00:39:32.760 --> 00:39:39.560 align:middle line:84%
then converting the
prices to weekly returns,

00:39:39.560 --> 00:39:43.440 align:middle line:84%
and then looking at how they're
correlated with each other.

00:39:43.440 --> 00:39:50.880 align:middle line:84%
So in this example, I believe it
was the Consumer Staples Sector

00:39:50.880 --> 00:39:57.280 align:middle line:84%
Fund, that I'm thinking of
regressing on the SPY, which

00:39:57.280 --> 00:40:03.280 align:middle line:84%
corresponds to the S&P 500;
MDY, which is a mid-cap index;

00:40:03.280 --> 00:40:07.160 align:middle line:90%
QQQ; and the Diamonds.

00:40:07.160 --> 00:40:10.800 align:middle line:84%
And if we look at these sort
of cumulative returns of these

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:18.320 align:middle line:84%
different ETFs, here's the
cumulative return over a 14-year

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:20.920 align:middle line:90%
period or something.

00:40:20.920 --> 00:40:25.160 align:middle line:84%
Well, any other--
any more thoughts

00:40:25.160 --> 00:40:31.760 align:middle line:84%
on why we might want to
regress this, on these indexes?

00:40:31.760 --> 00:40:33.160 align:middle line:90%
AJ?

00:40:33.160 --> 00:40:35.420 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The index
return should be--

00:40:35.420 --> 00:40:39.600 align:middle line:84%
the entire variance should be
explained by their sectors.

00:40:39.600 --> 00:40:41.880 align:middle line:84%
Assuming everything
in each index

00:40:41.880 --> 00:40:46.820 align:middle line:84%
is contained within
the market index,

00:40:46.820 --> 00:40:50.360 align:middle line:84%
it should explain perfectly
the variance in returns.

00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:51.360 align:middle line:90%
PETER KEMPTHORNE: Right.

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:53.820 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's looking at it
almost the other way around.

00:40:53.820 --> 00:40:58.280 align:middle line:84%
If we were looking
at the index ETF

00:40:58.280 --> 00:41:01.240 align:middle line:84%
as a function of the
sectors, we should

00:41:01.240 --> 00:41:04.360 align:middle line:84%
have almost a
perfect explanation

00:41:04.360 --> 00:41:07.040 align:middle line:90%
of that in a regression model.

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:10.040 align:middle line:84%
What can be useful
with this regression

00:41:10.040 --> 00:41:15.360 align:middle line:84%
is if we wanted to invest
in consumer staples

00:41:15.360 --> 00:41:19.760 align:middle line:84%
but we wanted to have
our investment be

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:26.660 align:middle line:84%
hedged against the market
risk, that is large.

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:34.120 align:middle line:84%
And so if we could eliminate
the dependence on the S&P 500,

00:41:34.120 --> 00:41:39.680 align:middle line:84%
eliminate the dependence on
the mid-cap and the QQQs,

00:41:39.680 --> 00:41:45.120 align:middle line:84%
then our hedged
investment, we'd be

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:49.680 align:middle line:84%
less concerned about
major drops in the market.

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:51.820 align:middle line:84%
So we'd be reducing
the market risk.

00:41:51.820 --> 00:41:55.960 align:middle line:84%
So this is where it
can be very useful.

00:41:55.960 --> 00:42:01.080 align:middle line:84%
Now, this kind of
approach has also

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:06.160 align:middle line:84%
been used to try and mimic
hedge fund strategies.

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:10.200 align:middle line:84%
And so there's some
papers out there

00:42:10.200 --> 00:42:17.040 align:middle line:84%
on hedge fund replication, where
hedge funds basically maybe

00:42:17.040 --> 00:42:23.280 align:middle line:84%
have most of their returns
attributable to liquid market

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:29.000 align:middle line:84%
instruments that one can
trade in a portfolio.

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:34.000 align:middle line:84%
And so hedge fund
replication methods

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:37.680 align:middle line:84%
have actually done that
kind of regression as well.

00:42:37.680 --> 00:42:42.700 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, with this,
with this setup,

00:42:42.700 --> 00:42:50.000 align:middle line:84%
we can just regress this
XLP on the index ETFs,

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:57.520 align:middle line:84%
and we get this regression
coefficient table here.

00:42:57.520 --> 00:43:04.720 align:middle line:84%
What's important to see
is whether the regression

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:09.160 align:middle line:84%
coefficients are significantly
different from zero or not.

00:43:09.160 --> 00:43:16.120 align:middle line:84%
And the t-value and
p-value columns basically

00:43:16.120 --> 00:43:20.120 align:middle line:84%
tell us that all of
these explanatory factors

00:43:20.120 --> 00:43:23.120 align:middle line:90%
are useful here.

00:43:23.120 --> 00:43:33.000 align:middle line:84%
And let's see,
when we study the--

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:33.680 align:middle line:90%
let's see.

00:43:33.680 --> 00:43:37.400 align:middle line:84%
When we study the
regression model--

00:43:37.400 --> 00:43:42.520 align:middle line:84%
OK, we have the R-squared
of this multiple regression.

00:43:42.520 --> 00:43:47.320 align:middle line:84%
The correlation of the fitted
and actual values is given by--

00:43:47.320 --> 00:43:52.000 align:middle line:84%
or the square of that is
given by the R-squared.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:58.000 align:middle line:84%
And we can do various regression
diagnostics which are used here.

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:01.020 align:middle line:84%
What-- I'll let you go
through these details.

00:44:01.020 --> 00:44:03.200 align:middle line:84%
It's a bit repetitive
from what we talked about

00:44:03.200 --> 00:44:04.840 align:middle line:90%
in the last lecture.

00:44:04.840 --> 00:44:07.760 align:middle line:90%
But let's see.

00:44:07.760 --> 00:44:16.480 align:middle line:84%
We can also model the
independent variables,

00:44:16.480 --> 00:44:20.720 align:middle line:84%
or do a principal components
analysis of those.

00:44:20.720 --> 00:44:24.720 align:middle line:84%
And if we compute a
principal component analysis

00:44:24.720 --> 00:44:27.140 align:middle line:84%
of our independent
variables-- in this case,

00:44:27.140 --> 00:44:32.480 align:middle line:84%
the index sector
exchange-traded funds--

00:44:32.480 --> 00:44:40.700 align:middle line:84%
we then have a sort of
decomposition of variability,

00:44:40.700 --> 00:44:43.440 align:middle line:84%
which indicates that the
first principal component

00:44:43.440 --> 00:44:48.360 align:middle line:84%
variable explains 90% of the
variability in these data,

00:44:48.360 --> 00:44:51.360 align:middle line:90%
the first two, 97%.

00:44:51.360 --> 00:44:54.160 align:middle line:84%
So we're actually explaining
a lot of variability

00:44:54.160 --> 00:44:56.280 align:middle line:90%
with just the first two.

00:44:56.280 --> 00:45:07.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, in looking at the
regression on the PC variables,

00:45:07.560 --> 00:45:18.320 align:middle line:84%
let's see, we can
consider the-- well,

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:21.240 align:middle line:84%
each of these PC variables,
Principal Component variables,

00:45:21.240 --> 00:45:23.480 align:middle line:90%
are orthogonal to each other.

00:45:23.480 --> 00:45:28.900 align:middle line:84%
So in estimating the
regression coefficients,

00:45:28.900 --> 00:45:41.800 align:middle line:84%
we can do so with simple linear
regressions of the ETF fund, y

00:45:41.800 --> 00:45:44.340 align:middle line:90%
on that, on each variable.

00:45:44.340 --> 00:45:48.560 align:middle line:84%
And so the first principal
component variable

00:45:48.560 --> 00:45:54.920 align:middle line:90%
has an R-squared of 0.545.

00:45:54.920 --> 00:45:58.840 align:middle line:84%
And the second principal
component variable

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:01.800 align:middle line:90%
has almost no correlation.

00:46:01.800 --> 00:46:07.260 align:middle line:84%
And so it's-- well,
it's almost none.

00:46:07.260 --> 00:46:11.640 align:middle line:84%
Its p-value is still 0.0518,
which is almost statistically

00:46:11.640 --> 00:46:12.520 align:middle line:90%
significant.

00:46:12.520 --> 00:46:18.320 align:middle line:84%
With very large samples, we're
able to judge small correlations

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:20.480 align:middle line:84%
as being statistically
significant,

00:46:20.480 --> 00:46:23.560 align:middle line:84%
but maybe it's not
practically significant.

00:46:23.560 --> 00:46:30.560 align:middle line:84%
And then the third has a
small R-squared as well,

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:34.600 align:middle line:84%
and the fourth,
again, rather small.

00:46:34.600 --> 00:46:44.830 align:middle line:84%
But what's of interest
is whether the--

00:46:44.830 --> 00:46:47.510 align:middle line:84%
or, it's basically just, How
statistically significant

00:46:47.510 --> 00:46:50.150 align:middle line:84%
are the principal
component variables?

00:46:50.150 --> 00:46:56.890 align:middle line:84%
And in the sort of
updated example, the--

00:46:56.890 --> 00:47:01.390 align:middle line:90%


00:47:01.390 --> 00:47:03.870 align:middle line:90%
let's see here.

00:47:03.870 --> 00:47:06.270 align:middle line:84%
Well, if we consider
the regression parameter

00:47:06.270 --> 00:47:10.750 align:middle line:84%
based on only the
first three variables,

00:47:10.750 --> 00:47:13.970 align:middle line:90%
we basically get these results.

00:47:13.970 --> 00:47:19.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, when I did this
a few years ago,

00:47:19.910 --> 00:47:27.990 align:middle line:84%
it ended up being the case
that the p-values for--

00:47:27.990 --> 00:47:31.590 align:middle line:84%
I think it was the second
principal component variable,

00:47:31.590 --> 00:47:34.350 align:middle line:90%
was not significant at all.

00:47:34.350 --> 00:47:42.950 align:middle line:84%
And so in choosing
what factors to include

00:47:42.950 --> 00:47:46.790 align:middle line:84%
in the model, the principal
components regression

00:47:46.790 --> 00:47:55.390 align:middle line:84%
approach of basically including
successive high-eigenvalue

00:47:55.390 --> 00:47:59.750 align:middle line:84%
principal component
variables in successively

00:47:59.750 --> 00:48:08.670 align:middle line:84%
so long as they're significant,
that actually sort of doesn't

00:48:08.670 --> 00:48:11.910 align:middle line:84%
include, really,
necessarily, the important

00:48:11.910 --> 00:48:14.510 align:middle line:90%
regressors in the model.

00:48:14.510 --> 00:48:18.150 align:middle line:84%
So we can have
statistically significant

00:48:18.150 --> 00:48:22.830 align:middle line:84%
high-order principal
component variables that

00:48:22.830 --> 00:48:25.410 align:middle line:84%
don't have much
variability in them,

00:48:25.410 --> 00:48:30.510 align:middle line:84%
but they actually are explaining
significant factors affecting

00:48:30.510 --> 00:48:32.950 align:middle line:90%
the response variable.

00:48:32.950 --> 00:48:37.470 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, this
note goes through

00:48:37.470 --> 00:48:46.630 align:middle line:84%
and additionally considers ridge
regression and lasso regression.

00:48:46.630 --> 00:48:53.830 align:middle line:84%
And so with the ridge
regression results,

00:48:53.830 --> 00:48:59.030 align:middle line:84%
the display of
regression parameters

00:48:59.030 --> 00:49:05.670 align:middle line:84%
is traced out as we consider
different constraints

00:49:05.670 --> 00:49:10.190 align:middle line:90%
on the L1--

00:49:10.190 --> 00:49:14.150 align:middle line:84%
or on the-- well,
on the L2 norm.

00:49:14.150 --> 00:49:20.270 align:middle line:84%
And if we look at the L1
norm of these estimates,

00:49:20.270 --> 00:49:25.590 align:middle line:84%
one can see, basically, how
as one sort of decreases

00:49:25.590 --> 00:49:32.390 align:middle line:84%
the penalty for the complexity
of the regression parameters,

00:49:32.390 --> 00:49:39.030 align:middle line:84%
we get final estimates given
by these ending values.

00:49:39.030 --> 00:49:42.610 align:middle line:84%
But if we increase
the penalty on those,

00:49:42.610 --> 00:49:46.830 align:middle line:84%
then they basically are
shrinking towards zero.

00:49:46.830 --> 00:49:50.230 align:middle line:84%
Although, the shrinkage isn't
necessarily in a monotone

00:49:50.230 --> 00:49:52.070 align:middle line:90%
manner.

00:49:52.070 --> 00:49:56.750 align:middle line:84%
And then if we look at
the lasso regression,

00:49:56.750 --> 00:50:01.630 align:middle line:84%
with a same L1-norm
sort of scaling,

00:50:01.630 --> 00:50:06.630 align:middle line:84%
one can see how, as that
lambda parameter associated

00:50:06.630 --> 00:50:13.510 align:middle line:84%
with the penalty is
increased, we basically

00:50:13.510 --> 00:50:19.630 align:middle line:84%
have the L1 norm getting
smaller, of the resulting

00:50:19.630 --> 00:50:20.790 align:middle line:90%
estimates.

00:50:20.790 --> 00:50:24.270 align:middle line:90%
And this shows you how--

00:50:24.270 --> 00:50:27.830 align:middle line:84%
I guess the third
variable is the first

00:50:27.830 --> 00:50:36.710 align:middle line:84%
to be excluded, then the second,
and then, finally, the fourth.

00:50:36.710 --> 00:50:39.930 align:middle line:90%
So, all right.

00:50:39.930 --> 00:50:44.030 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so this note
goes through an illustration

00:50:44.030 --> 00:50:48.470 align:middle line:84%
of lasso and principal
components regression.

00:50:48.470 --> 00:50:52.150 align:middle line:84%
And it also provided
a comparison

00:50:52.150 --> 00:50:56.390 align:middle line:84%
of different
coefficients by method.

00:50:56.390 --> 00:51:03.950 align:middle line:84%
And what this final chart
shows is the comparison

00:51:03.950 --> 00:51:09.150 align:middle line:90%
of beta estimates by method.

00:51:09.150 --> 00:51:14.190 align:middle line:84%
And one can see that most of the
methods give similar results,

00:51:14.190 --> 00:51:18.270 align:middle line:84%
but using just the first three
principal component variables

00:51:18.270 --> 00:51:21.750 align:middle line:84%
gives us very
different estimates

00:51:21.750 --> 00:51:23.330 align:middle line:90%
of regression parameters.

00:51:23.330 --> 00:51:34.150 align:middle line:84%
So there's sensitivity of
the estimators to the data.

00:51:34.150 --> 00:51:39.840 align:middle line:90%
And it's perhaps useful to--

00:51:39.840 --> 00:51:42.550 align:middle line:90%


00:51:42.550 --> 00:51:44.150 align:middle line:90%
let's see.

00:51:44.150 --> 00:51:46.830 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's useful to
consider these alternatives.

00:51:46.830 --> 00:51:49.390 align:middle line:84%
With very large sample
sizes, you generally

00:51:49.390 --> 00:51:53.630 align:middle line:84%
don't get much difference in
the ridge or the Lasso results.

00:51:53.630 --> 00:51:58.750 align:middle line:84%
It's usually in smaller sample
sizes that you get differences.

00:51:58.750 --> 00:52:04.530 align:middle line:84%
With the principal components
regression, in this example,

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:08.710 align:middle line:84%
the first three principal
component variables

00:52:08.710 --> 00:52:13.190 align:middle line:84%
end up giving estimates,
that are in the yellow.

00:52:13.190 --> 00:52:17.150 align:middle line:84%
But if we chose which principal
component variables to include

00:52:17.150 --> 00:52:21.830 align:middle line:84%
based on their
statistical significance,

00:52:21.830 --> 00:52:28.670 align:middle line:84%
then the more significant
principal component variables

00:52:28.670 --> 00:52:35.230 align:middle line:84%
ended up leading to
this green values, which

00:52:35.230 --> 00:52:37.590 align:middle line:90%
are comparable to the others.

00:52:37.590 --> 00:52:43.190 align:middle line:90%
So this suggests that--

00:52:43.190 --> 00:52:47.430 align:middle line:84%
well, actually in this
case, the green values

00:52:47.430 --> 00:52:51.250 align:middle line:84%
are equal to least
squares, just because all

00:52:51.250 --> 00:52:52.750 align:middle line:84%
of the principal
component variables

00:52:52.750 --> 00:52:56.350 align:middle line:90%
were statistically significant.

00:52:56.350 --> 00:52:58.870 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:52:58.870 --> 00:53:08.430 align:middle line:84%
Well, the next thing
I wanted to go through

00:53:08.430 --> 00:53:14.470 align:middle line:84%
is this linear regression
modeling for the capital asset

00:53:14.470 --> 00:53:16.350 align:middle line:90%
pricing model.

00:53:16.350 --> 00:53:23.710 align:middle line:84%
And in this note, we first
review what the capital asset

00:53:23.710 --> 00:53:28.710 align:middle line:84%
pricing model is, how it relates
to returns on stocks and returns

00:53:28.710 --> 00:53:31.350 align:middle line:90%
on market index.

00:53:31.350 --> 00:53:39.350 align:middle line:84%
And what we're going to do is
go through the computation,

00:53:39.350 --> 00:53:42.950 align:middle line:84%
computations, involved
with an empirical analysis

00:53:42.950 --> 00:53:46.550 align:middle line:84%
of this capital
asset pricing model,

00:53:46.550 --> 00:53:50.110 align:middle line:84%
and then consider
testing hypotheses

00:53:50.110 --> 00:53:54.710 align:middle line:84%
about individual
coefficients, and then

00:53:54.710 --> 00:53:59.590 align:middle line:84%
conclude with actually fitting
this capital asset pricing

00:53:59.590 --> 00:54:05.470 align:middle line:84%
model to all stocks
in the S&P 500 index,

00:54:05.470 --> 00:54:09.630 align:middle line:84%
and comparing the results
of the capital asset pricing

00:54:09.630 --> 00:54:12.750 align:middle line:90%
model parameters for that.

00:54:12.750 --> 00:54:19.790 align:middle line:84%
So with this, we begin with
basically a description

00:54:19.790 --> 00:54:23.310 align:middle line:84%
of what the capital
asset pricing model is.

00:54:23.310 --> 00:54:26.570 align:middle line:84%
We went through this, I
think, in our third lecture,

00:54:26.570 --> 00:54:31.390 align:middle line:84%
which says that in
an efficient market,

00:54:31.390 --> 00:54:37.710 align:middle line:84%
the expected return
of a stock, asset j,

00:54:37.710 --> 00:54:41.830 align:middle line:84%
should equal the
risk-free return

00:54:41.830 --> 00:54:50.230 align:middle line:84%
plus a beta factor times the
excess return of the market.

00:54:50.230 --> 00:55:00.270 align:middle line:84%
And so beta j is sort of
the market risk factor.

00:55:00.270 --> 00:55:05.750 align:middle line:84%
And the excess return
of the market portfolio

00:55:05.750 --> 00:55:10.790 align:middle line:84%
is simply how much bigger
that market return is compared

00:55:10.790 --> 00:55:12.750 align:middle line:90%
with the risk-free rate.

00:55:12.750 --> 00:55:18.550 align:middle line:84%
Now, with these
parameters, if we

00:55:18.550 --> 00:55:26.070 align:middle line:84%
have data consisting of
empirical returns R for stocks

00:55:26.070 --> 00:55:29.630 align:middle line:84%
j at different times
t, different values

00:55:29.630 --> 00:55:33.510 align:middle line:84%
over t of the
risk-free rate, and we

00:55:33.510 --> 00:55:38.910 align:middle line:84%
consider the excess
return of each asset

00:55:38.910 --> 00:55:42.030 align:middle line:84%
and the excess
return of the market,

00:55:42.030 --> 00:55:51.030 align:middle line:84%
then this data can be used to
specify a linear regression

00:55:51.030 --> 00:55:59.070 align:middle line:84%
model where we have an intercept
alpha j and a slope beta

00:55:59.070 --> 00:56:03.170 align:middle line:90%
j for the regression.

00:56:03.170 --> 00:56:13.100 align:middle line:84%
So we're looking here at R star
market, and this is R star j.

00:56:13.100 --> 00:56:15.750 align:middle line:90%


00:56:15.750 --> 00:56:27.830 align:middle line:84%
And we'll plot values over
time t of these excess returns.

00:56:27.830 --> 00:56:32.750 align:middle line:84%
And we can basically
fit a regression model

00:56:32.750 --> 00:56:34.870 align:middle line:90%
where we have y hat--

00:56:34.870 --> 00:56:45.230 align:middle line:84%
or R star jt is equal to
alpha j plus beta j R star mt.

00:56:45.230 --> 00:56:51.430 align:middle line:84%
And if the capital asset
pricing model holds,

00:56:51.430 --> 00:57:00.110 align:middle line:84%
then the alpha j's should be
0, because the alpha j's--

00:57:00.110 --> 00:57:03.990 align:middle line:84%
if we take the expectation
in this equation

00:57:03.990 --> 00:57:10.470 align:middle line:84%
with residuals that are
mean 0 constant variance,

00:57:10.470 --> 00:57:15.030 align:middle line:84%
then we get the capital
asset pricing model equation

00:57:15.030 --> 00:57:19.510 align:middle line:90%
when the alpha j is equal to 0.

00:57:19.510 --> 00:57:25.140 align:middle line:84%
So what we can do with
real data is fit this model

00:57:25.140 --> 00:57:29.260 align:middle line:84%
and then test whether
alpha j is 0 or not.

00:57:29.260 --> 00:57:35.440 align:middle line:84%
And if it is consistent
with a 0 value,

00:57:35.440 --> 00:57:39.940 align:middle line:84%
then the pricing
of the asset can

00:57:39.940 --> 00:57:44.460 align:middle line:84%
be judged to be sort
of in an equilibrium

00:57:44.460 --> 00:57:48.300 align:middle line:84%
described by the capital
asset pricing model.

00:57:48.300 --> 00:57:52.300 align:middle line:90%
And so let's take a look.

00:57:52.300 --> 00:57:55.660 align:middle line:84%
I think what's
perhaps useful is just

00:57:55.660 --> 00:58:01.080 align:middle line:84%
to see the code for
doing these computations.

00:58:01.080 --> 00:58:05.740 align:middle line:90%
It's included in the note here.

00:58:05.740 --> 00:58:11.500 align:middle line:84%
But if we pick a
particular stock, GE stock,

00:58:11.500 --> 00:58:17.860 align:middle line:84%
and fit the regression model,
we basically-- in this code,

00:58:17.860 --> 00:58:20.820 align:middle line:84%
the only thing we
need to do is specify

00:58:20.820 --> 00:58:29.500 align:middle line:84%
the symbol for the stock, and
then extract from our data

00:58:29.500 --> 00:58:39.260 align:middle line:84%
object the excess market return
and the excess asset return.

00:58:39.260 --> 00:58:41.300 align:middle line:84%
And then fit that
regression, and we get

00:58:41.300 --> 00:58:44.020 align:middle line:90%
these coefficients table here.

00:58:44.020 --> 00:58:50.660 align:middle line:84%
Now, in this example,
the intercept coefficient

00:58:50.660 --> 00:58:53.580 align:middle line:90%
is the estimate of alpha.

00:58:53.580 --> 00:58:58.940 align:middle line:84%
And if GE is being priced
consistent with the capital

00:58:58.940 --> 00:59:03.140 align:middle line:84%
asset pricing model,
then that estimate

00:59:03.140 --> 00:59:05.460 align:middle line:84%
should be consistent
with the null value.

00:59:05.460 --> 00:59:10.060 align:middle line:84%
And the p-value for testing
whether that intercept is 0

00:59:10.060 --> 00:59:14.060 align:middle line:84%
or not gives us evidence
supporting the capital asset

00:59:14.060 --> 00:59:16.340 align:middle line:90%
pricing model.

00:59:16.340 --> 00:59:21.580 align:middle line:84%
Now, the market, the
excess return of the market

00:59:21.580 --> 00:59:26.360 align:middle line:84%
has an estimate that's about
1, with some standard error.

00:59:26.360 --> 00:59:29.580 align:middle line:84%
It has a huge t-value
and a huge p-value.

00:59:29.580 --> 00:59:35.100 align:middle line:84%
Those values being
large, or a huge t-value

00:59:35.100 --> 00:59:37.740 align:middle line:84%
and very small p-value,
are not surprising at all,

00:59:37.740 --> 00:59:40.060 align:middle line:90%
just because they're correlated.

00:59:40.060 --> 00:59:45.580 align:middle line:84%
And a 0 value for the slope
is sort of meaningless here.

00:59:45.580 --> 00:59:51.900 align:middle line:84%
What could be useful is testing
whether our beta coefficient

00:59:51.900 --> 00:59:57.660 align:middle line:84%
is consistent with sort of the
average market risk of beta

00:59:57.660 --> 01:00:01.340 align:middle line:90%
equal to 1, or not.

01:00:01.340 --> 01:00:05.540 align:middle line:84%
But here's basically a plot
of the linear regression

01:00:05.540 --> 01:00:10.140 align:middle line:84%
model for GE, and
a discussion just

01:00:10.140 --> 01:00:16.220 align:middle line:84%
of getting comfortable
with R-squared values

01:00:16.220 --> 01:00:21.610 align:middle line:84%
and calibrating our views of
scatter plots to those values.

01:00:21.610 --> 01:00:24.860 align:middle line:90%


01:00:24.860 --> 01:00:27.640 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
residuals analysis,

01:00:27.640 --> 01:00:29.420 align:middle line:90%
that is very important.

01:00:29.420 --> 01:00:34.820 align:middle line:84%
As I introduced at the beginning
of our regression study,

01:00:34.820 --> 01:00:38.340 align:middle line:84%
we make assumptions
about our model.

01:00:38.340 --> 01:00:41.340 align:middle line:84%
And we then, once
we fit the model,

01:00:41.340 --> 01:00:44.460 align:middle line:84%
we check our assumptions to
see whether those are satisfied

01:00:44.460 --> 01:00:45.540 align:middle line:90%
or not.

01:00:45.540 --> 01:00:53.140 align:middle line:84%
And in this case, we might
assume that the residuals

01:00:53.140 --> 01:00:55.620 align:middle line:90%
are normally distributed.

01:00:55.620 --> 01:01:02.260 align:middle line:84%
And here's a histogram of
the residuals from this GE

01:01:02.260 --> 01:01:03.580 align:middle line:90%
regression.

01:01:03.580 --> 01:01:08.020 align:middle line:84%
And there actually are two
bell-shaped curves here.

01:01:08.020 --> 01:01:12.020 align:middle line:84%
There's one, that's in
green, that corresponds

01:01:12.020 --> 01:01:15.620 align:middle line:84%
to the maximum likelihood
estimate of the mean

01:01:15.620 --> 01:01:19.580 align:middle line:90%
and variance of that normal.

01:01:19.580 --> 01:01:23.700 align:middle line:84%
But there's also a
blue curve, which

01:01:23.700 --> 01:01:27.980 align:middle line:84%
corresponds to a
robust estimator

01:01:27.980 --> 01:01:30.940 align:middle line:84%
of the normal
distribution parameters.

01:01:30.940 --> 01:01:35.680 align:middle line:84%
So, and we just talked a bit
about normal linear regressions

01:01:35.680 --> 01:01:36.900 align:middle line:90%
and their being optimal.

01:01:36.900 --> 01:01:40.260 align:middle line:84%
Well, they're optimal so long
as the normal distribution

01:01:40.260 --> 01:01:41.900 align:middle line:90%
is applied.

01:01:41.900 --> 01:01:46.780 align:middle line:84%
And one can calculate
what's called

01:01:46.780 --> 01:01:51.820 align:middle line:90%
a QQ plot, of the residuals.

01:01:51.820 --> 01:01:57.140 align:middle line:84%
Where the theoretical
distribution is normal,

01:01:57.140 --> 01:02:03.140 align:middle line:84%
we can think of ordered
samples of normals,

01:02:03.140 --> 01:02:05.340 align:middle line:84%
from smallest to
largest, and pair

01:02:05.340 --> 01:02:07.300 align:middle line:84%
those with our
ordered residuals,

01:02:07.300 --> 01:02:09.580 align:middle line:90%
from smallest to largest.

01:02:09.580 --> 01:02:12.080 align:middle line:84%
And this plot will look
like a straight line

01:02:12.080 --> 01:02:16.660 align:middle line:90%
if the residuals are Gaussian.

01:02:16.660 --> 01:02:25.620 align:middle line:84%
And the green line corresponds
to the MLE fit of the Gaussian.

01:02:25.620 --> 01:02:30.260 align:middle line:84%
Basically, the slope will
equal the standard deviation

01:02:30.260 --> 01:02:33.820 align:middle line:84%
of the distribution,
and the median roughly

01:02:33.820 --> 01:02:38.060 align:middle line:84%
will correspond
to the mean value.

01:02:38.060 --> 01:02:43.020 align:middle line:84%
But what we have is
a robust estimate

01:02:43.020 --> 01:02:49.380 align:middle line:84%
of the standard deviation
of the residuals,

01:02:49.380 --> 01:02:51.500 align:middle line:90%
gives us this blue line.

01:02:51.500 --> 01:02:56.500 align:middle line:84%
And the robust estimate
of the residual variance

01:02:56.500 --> 01:03:00.780 align:middle line:84%
is based on the interquartile
range of the residuals.

01:03:00.780 --> 01:03:05.220 align:middle line:84%
So the middle 50%, what
kind of standard deviation

01:03:05.220 --> 01:03:11.300 align:middle line:84%
would match the middle 50%
range of the residuals?

01:03:11.300 --> 01:03:18.020 align:middle line:84%
And there's an argument
that this robust estimate

01:03:18.020 --> 01:03:20.540 align:middle line:90%
might in fact be better.

01:03:20.540 --> 01:03:24.620 align:middle line:84%
And another way of
evaluating the residuals

01:03:24.620 --> 01:03:32.580 align:middle line:84%
is to compute fitted percentiles
under the residual model.

01:03:32.580 --> 01:03:38.460 align:middle line:84%
So if we observe an
epsilon hat with mean mu

01:03:38.460 --> 01:03:42.900 align:middle line:84%
hat and standard
deviation sigma hat,

01:03:42.900 --> 01:03:49.500 align:middle line:84%
we can do the inverse of the
probability integral transform

01:03:49.500 --> 01:03:57.340 align:middle line:84%
and get the percentile
of that outcome.

01:03:57.340 --> 01:04:03.340 align:middle line:84%
And so it turns out
that these percentiles

01:04:03.340 --> 01:04:09.380 align:middle line:84%
should be uniformly distributed,
from, like, 1 to 99,

01:04:09.380 --> 01:04:13.780 align:middle line:90%
if this normal model is correct.

01:04:13.780 --> 01:04:19.060 align:middle line:84%
And so we can actually consider
different estimates of sigma

01:04:19.060 --> 01:04:24.500 align:middle line:90%
hat, from robust to MLE.

01:04:24.500 --> 01:04:27.940 align:middle line:84%
And with the MLE,
here's the histogram

01:04:27.940 --> 01:04:33.460 align:middle line:90%
of the fitted percentiles.

01:04:33.460 --> 01:04:39.220 align:middle line:84%
It's basically
underestimating percentiles

01:04:39.220 --> 01:04:41.180 align:middle line:90%
that are close to the mean--

01:04:41.180 --> 01:04:43.020 align:middle line:90%
or the median.

01:04:43.020 --> 01:04:49.300 align:middle line:84%
And so it really isn't fitting
the residuals very well

01:04:49.300 --> 01:04:51.620 align:middle line:90%
across the whole range.

01:04:51.620 --> 01:04:55.340 align:middle line:84%
And if instead we consider
fitted percentiles

01:04:55.340 --> 01:05:00.340 align:middle line:84%
from the robust estimate
of the variance,

01:05:00.340 --> 01:05:06.540 align:middle line:84%
then the fitted percentiles
of the residuals

01:05:06.540 --> 01:05:11.860 align:middle line:84%
is consistent with uniform
in the middle of the data,

01:05:11.860 --> 01:05:16.700 align:middle line:84%
except in the top 1%
and the bottom 1%.

01:05:16.700 --> 01:05:20.540 align:middle line:84%
So it's very possible
that our data

01:05:20.540 --> 01:05:24.140 align:middle line:84%
has a non-normal residual
distribution or error

01:05:24.140 --> 01:05:26.860 align:middle line:90%
distribution.

01:05:26.860 --> 01:05:29.700 align:middle line:84%
And perhaps that
non-normal distribution

01:05:29.700 --> 01:05:34.580 align:middle line:84%
could be well modeled
with a mixture model.

01:05:34.580 --> 01:05:39.540 align:middle line:84%
Now, OK, there's regression
diagnostics, which

01:05:39.540 --> 01:05:40.710 align:middle line:90%
I'll let you read through.

01:05:40.710 --> 01:05:45.860 align:middle line:90%


01:05:45.860 --> 01:05:48.620 align:middle line:84%
And then there's this
section on testing hypotheses

01:05:48.620 --> 01:05:52.380 align:middle line:84%
about individual
model coefficients.

01:05:52.380 --> 01:05:53.140 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

01:05:53.140 --> 01:05:56.480 align:middle line:84%
If you have this
on your computer,

01:05:56.480 --> 01:05:58.140 align:middle line:84%
you can probably see
it a little better

01:05:58.140 --> 01:06:00.200 align:middle line:90%
than seeing this screen here.

01:06:00.200 --> 01:06:02.900 align:middle line:90%
But with the normal--

01:06:02.900 --> 01:06:08.420 align:middle line:84%
or with our testing of
individual coefficients,

01:06:08.420 --> 01:06:14.460 align:middle line:84%
we basically use the fact that
our least squares estimator

01:06:14.460 --> 01:06:19.820 align:middle line:84%
is multivariate normal with
mean equal to the true beta

01:06:19.820 --> 01:06:24.340 align:middle line:84%
vector and covariance
matrix, given here.

01:06:24.340 --> 01:06:31.340 align:middle line:84%
So, so we can make various
tests of different regression

01:06:31.340 --> 01:06:32.420 align:middle line:90%
parameters.

01:06:32.420 --> 01:06:36.460 align:middle line:84%
So we have the t-statistics
for testing whether a parameter

01:06:36.460 --> 01:06:42.820 align:middle line:84%
value is 0 or not, and
use the t-distribution

01:06:42.820 --> 01:06:45.940 align:middle line:84%
to judge how statistically
significant that is.

01:06:45.940 --> 01:06:48.360 align:middle line:84%
In our capital asset
pricing model case,

01:06:48.360 --> 01:06:51.900 align:middle line:84%
we actually are interested in
testing whether the alphas are

01:06:51.900 --> 01:06:54.860 align:middle line:90%
zero or not.

01:06:54.860 --> 01:06:58.700 align:middle line:84%
And one could also
consider testing for

01:06:58.700 --> 01:07:01.520 align:middle line:84%
whether the beta factor
is equal to 1 or not.

01:07:01.520 --> 01:07:03.660 align:middle line:84%
1, for the beta,
is actually what

01:07:03.660 --> 01:07:07.300 align:middle line:84%
the average beta is across
all stocks in the market.

01:07:07.300 --> 01:07:13.820 align:middle line:84%
And so one can consider judging
whether assets sort of have

01:07:13.820 --> 01:07:18.700 align:middle line:84%
significantly high risk,
high betas, or low betas,

01:07:18.700 --> 01:07:25.700 align:middle line:84%
using a test of whether
the estimated regression

01:07:25.700 --> 01:07:29.860 align:middle line:84%
coefficient is significantly
different from 1 or not.

01:07:29.860 --> 01:07:38.340 align:middle line:84%
And so with this, I've
basically computed this for GE.

01:07:38.340 --> 01:07:51.980 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out that, I
guess, the t-stat for GE,

01:07:51.980 --> 01:07:57.580 align:middle line:84%
which corresponds to a beta of
1.083, that's fairly close to 1,

01:07:57.580 --> 01:08:01.620 align:middle line:84%
in terms of absolute magnitude,
but it's actually a bit--

01:08:01.620 --> 01:08:04.140 align:middle line:84%
it's statistically
significant, according

01:08:04.140 --> 01:08:07.490 align:middle line:90%
to the arguments given here.

01:08:07.490 --> 01:08:14.090 align:middle line:84%
Now, there are many packages
in R, but one of them

01:08:14.090 --> 01:08:17.090 align:middle line:84%
is the CAR package,
which allows one

01:08:17.090 --> 01:08:21.050 align:middle line:84%
to conduct tests of linear
hypotheses like these.

01:08:21.050 --> 01:08:25.689 align:middle line:84%
And so it goes
through and performs

01:08:25.689 --> 01:08:29.930 align:middle line:84%
the same kinds of tests for
whether the intercept is 0

01:08:29.930 --> 01:08:31.450 align:middle line:90%
or not.

01:08:31.450 --> 01:08:35.210 align:middle line:84%
And in implementing
these hypothesis tests,

01:08:35.210 --> 01:08:40.850 align:middle line:84%
this CAR package uses the
sort of F-test approach.

01:08:40.850 --> 01:08:46.250 align:middle line:84%
So one has results that give
us different residual sum

01:08:46.250 --> 01:08:53.370 align:middle line:84%
of squares and F-statistics, and
p-values for the F-statistics

01:08:53.370 --> 01:08:55.770 align:middle line:90%
corresponding to these.

01:08:55.770 --> 01:08:58.290 align:middle line:90%
Now, let's see.

01:08:58.290 --> 01:09:01.450 align:middle line:90%
With-- let's see.

01:09:01.450 --> 01:09:07.090 align:middle line:84%
Before showing the results for
all the stocks in the S&P 500,

01:09:07.090 --> 01:09:14.290 align:middle line:84%
there's another note on
regression analysis hypothesis

01:09:14.290 --> 01:09:16.609 align:middle line:90%
testing.

01:09:16.609 --> 01:09:21.649 align:middle line:84%
And what's interesting
to think about

01:09:21.649 --> 01:09:28.090 align:middle line:84%
is we can consider testing
whether a submodel,

01:09:28.090 --> 01:09:33.609 align:middle line:84%
a model without as many
factors in it, is suitable.

01:09:33.609 --> 01:09:36.970 align:middle line:84%
But one can also test
for whether there's

01:09:36.970 --> 01:09:42.870 align:middle line:84%
a change in model
parameters with a regime,

01:09:42.870 --> 01:09:48.569 align:middle line:84%
so that maybe there's an initial
period with a given set of model

01:09:48.569 --> 01:09:53.010 align:middle line:84%
parameters, and then a
regime shift following

01:09:53.010 --> 01:09:56.530 align:middle line:84%
that, where the parameter
values have changed.

01:09:56.530 --> 01:10:00.850 align:middle line:84%
And so the mathematical
theory for this

01:10:00.850 --> 01:10:07.730 align:middle line:84%
is covered in section 3, and
one can consider testing--

01:10:07.730 --> 01:10:09.550 align:middle line:84%
with the capital
asset pricing model,

01:10:09.550 --> 01:10:12.970 align:middle line:84%
maybe-- whether there's a
change in regression parameters

01:10:12.970 --> 01:10:15.530 align:middle line:90%
over an entire period.

01:10:15.530 --> 01:10:23.230 align:middle line:84%
And so what I want to
just go to is the results.

01:10:23.230 --> 01:10:30.170 align:middle line:84%
Actually, the linear algebra for
these hypothesis testing methods

01:10:30.170 --> 01:10:34.090 align:middle line:90%
is very straightforward.

01:10:34.090 --> 01:10:37.130 align:middle line:84%
And I encourage you
to read through these,

01:10:37.130 --> 01:10:41.170 align:middle line:90%
just to see how they play out.

01:10:41.170 --> 01:10:45.110 align:middle line:90%
But let's see.

01:10:45.110 --> 01:10:50.410 align:middle line:84%
What's interesting, I guess,
is, with this change between two

01:10:50.410 --> 01:10:55.990 align:middle line:84%
periods, if we consider sort of
an original regression model,

01:10:55.990 --> 01:11:01.250 align:middle line:84%
y equals X beta plus epsilon
for a very long period,

01:11:01.250 --> 01:11:03.410 align:middle line:84%
we might consider
splitting it up

01:11:03.410 --> 01:11:08.210 align:middle line:84%
into the first part, period A,
and the second part, period B,

01:11:08.210 --> 01:11:14.010 align:middle line:84%
and have two equations for
the respective sets of data.

01:11:14.010 --> 01:11:21.770 align:middle line:84%
And in thinking about
the two periods,

01:11:21.770 --> 01:11:27.210 align:middle line:84%
we basically can test whether
the regression parameters

01:11:27.210 --> 01:11:29.730 align:middle line:84%
for the second period are
the same as the regression

01:11:29.730 --> 01:11:33.690 align:middle line:90%
parameters for the first period.

01:11:33.690 --> 01:11:39.210 align:middle line:84%
And we can write out
the model equations

01:11:39.210 --> 01:11:40.416 align:middle line:90%
with appropriate matrices.

01:11:40.416 --> 01:11:43.770 align:middle line:90%


01:11:43.770 --> 01:11:48.770 align:middle line:84%
And then we basically
have an F-test statistic

01:11:48.770 --> 01:11:54.130 align:middle line:84%
for seeing whether these
regression parameters are

01:11:54.130 --> 01:11:56.530 align:middle line:90%
different or not.

01:11:56.530 --> 01:12:01.970 align:middle line:90%
And one can also--

01:12:01.970 --> 01:12:08.450 align:middle line:84%
instead of considering separate
parameters for each period,

01:12:08.450 --> 01:12:19.270 align:middle line:84%
one can consider a beta value
here for the entire period,

01:12:19.270 --> 01:12:23.930 align:middle line:84%
and then use that
beta value together

01:12:23.930 --> 01:12:29.890 align:middle line:84%
with the change in
parameter values in period B

01:12:29.890 --> 01:12:33.730 align:middle line:84%
from period A. And
so one can set up

01:12:33.730 --> 01:12:37.650 align:middle line:84%
the regression
model where one is

01:12:37.650 --> 01:12:40.810 align:middle line:84%
interested in whether
this change parameter

01:12:40.810 --> 01:12:44.770 align:middle line:90%
delta is equal to 0 or not.

01:12:44.770 --> 01:12:49.730 align:middle line:84%
And so, mathematically,
we get F-test from that.

01:12:49.730 --> 01:12:55.730 align:middle line:84%
Now, with the GE stock
I subjectively chose

01:12:55.730 --> 01:13:01.290 align:middle line:84%
this period split
for A from B. If we

01:13:01.290 --> 01:13:07.770 align:middle line:84%
look at the cumulative sum
of standardized residuals

01:13:07.770 --> 01:13:11.970 align:middle line:84%
from the regression
model, then we basically

01:13:11.970 --> 01:13:16.930 align:middle line:84%
have residuals that are
consistently negative,

01:13:16.930 --> 01:13:21.450 align:middle line:84%
cumulating to a lower
value around 2019,

01:13:21.450 --> 01:13:24.930 align:middle line:84%
and then later
expanding beyond that.

01:13:24.930 --> 01:13:31.956 align:middle line:84%
So this sort of time series
of accumulated residuals

01:13:31.956 --> 01:13:34.810 align:middle line:84%
sort of highlights that
there's strong time

01:13:34.810 --> 01:13:38.450 align:middle line:90%
dependence in the residuals.

01:13:38.450 --> 01:13:41.810 align:middle line:84%
But if we fit the
regression models to these--

01:13:41.810 --> 01:13:44.650 align:middle line:84%
separate regression models
to these two periods,

01:13:44.650 --> 01:13:49.090 align:middle line:84%
we end up getting highly
significant results

01:13:49.090 --> 01:13:52.990 align:middle line:84%
for the change in
the two periods.

01:13:52.990 --> 01:13:55.130 align:middle line:84%
There's basically
an intercept, which

01:13:55.130 --> 01:13:59.450 align:middle line:84%
is the alpha, which changes
from negative to positive,

01:13:59.450 --> 01:14:05.330 align:middle line:84%
and the market risk
basically changes

01:14:05.330 --> 01:14:13.010 align:middle line:84%
from 0.773 beta in
the first period,

01:14:13.010 --> 01:14:19.190 align:middle line:84%
to 0.773 plus 0.3537
in the second period.

01:14:19.190 --> 01:14:23.970 align:middle line:84%
So these capital
asset pricing models

01:14:23.970 --> 01:14:27.210 align:middle line:84%
are not expected, perhaps,
to hold over really, really

01:14:27.210 --> 01:14:28.850 align:middle line:90%
long periods of time.

01:14:28.850 --> 01:14:33.570 align:middle line:84%
And if we wanted
to apply them, we'd

01:14:33.570 --> 01:14:37.930 align:middle line:84%
likely sort of choose a rolling
window approach perhaps,

01:14:37.930 --> 01:14:39.370 align:middle line:84%
which then leads
to questions of,

01:14:39.370 --> 01:14:42.270 align:middle line:84%
how do we decide on what
rolling window is appropriate,

01:14:42.270 --> 01:14:45.610 align:middle line:84%
and opens up other
issues to study.

01:14:45.610 --> 01:14:51.810 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so with
that background

01:14:51.810 --> 01:14:54.690 align:middle line:84%
for hypothesis
testing, let's go back

01:14:54.690 --> 01:14:59.690 align:middle line:84%
to fitting the capital
asset pricing model

01:14:59.690 --> 01:15:05.170 align:middle line:90%
to all stocks in the S&P 500.

01:15:05.170 --> 01:15:06.130 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

01:15:06.130 --> 01:15:10.330 align:middle line:84%
The code here basically fits
this capital asset pricing model

01:15:10.330 --> 01:15:18.250 align:middle line:84%
regression for all the stocks
that have data going back

01:15:18.250 --> 01:15:19.690 align:middle line:90%
several years.

01:15:19.690 --> 01:15:25.010 align:middle line:84%
So there were, I think,
around 380 or 400 stocks.

01:15:25.010 --> 01:15:29.290 align:middle line:90%
And they're grouped by sector.

01:15:29.290 --> 01:15:35.090 align:middle line:84%
And we can see how the
R-squareds of the regressions

01:15:35.090 --> 01:15:39.250 align:middle line:90%
vary from 0 to 1.

01:15:39.250 --> 01:15:42.530 align:middle line:90%
They typically are above 0.2.

01:15:42.530 --> 01:15:47.890 align:middle line:84%
So there's some reasonable
R-squared relationships

01:15:47.890 --> 01:15:50.970 align:middle line:90%
that are being explained.

01:15:50.970 --> 01:15:58.250 align:middle line:84%
And if we look at the
alphas by sector--

01:15:58.250 --> 01:16:03.730 align:middle line:84%
here's sort of parallel
box plots of the alphas,

01:16:03.730 --> 01:16:07.370 align:middle line:84%
the alpha estimates within
each of the sectors.

01:16:07.370 --> 01:16:13.040 align:middle line:84%
And so this
highlights how some--

01:16:13.040 --> 01:16:16.890 align:middle line:90%


01:16:16.890 --> 01:16:22.050 align:middle line:84%
let's see-- some sectors,
like, I guess, construction,

01:16:22.050 --> 01:16:27.890 align:middle line:84%
sort of had positive alphas,
as did computer technology.

01:16:27.890 --> 01:16:30.570 align:middle line:90%


01:16:30.570 --> 01:16:31.110 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

01:16:31.110 --> 01:16:36.890 align:middle line:84%
The conglomerates tended to
have negative alphas there.

01:16:36.890 --> 01:16:42.850 align:middle line:84%
And we can calculate
the p-values

01:16:42.850 --> 01:16:47.970 align:middle line:84%
for testing whether the alphas
are consistent with 0 or not.

01:16:47.970 --> 01:16:55.690 align:middle line:84%
And this graph here
shows how the p-values

01:16:55.690 --> 01:17:04.610 align:middle line:84%
for almost all the stocks exceed
the p-value threshold of 0.05.

01:17:04.610 --> 01:17:14.850 align:middle line:84%
So if we can't reject the null
hypothesis of alpha equaling 0,

01:17:14.850 --> 01:17:18.210 align:middle line:90%
the p-value is above 0.05.

01:17:18.210 --> 01:17:22.290 align:middle line:84%
And one can see that
there's basically

01:17:22.290 --> 01:17:25.410 align:middle line:84%
sort of a handful, or
a couple of handful,

01:17:25.410 --> 01:17:29.970 align:middle line:84%
of stocks that have
a significant alpha.

01:17:29.970 --> 01:17:33.730 align:middle line:84%
And if we use a 5%
threshold, well, we'd

01:17:33.730 --> 01:17:38.690 align:middle line:84%
expect 5% of the results to
be statistically significant,

01:17:38.690 --> 01:17:41.570 align:middle line:84%
when there's no
statistical significance.

01:17:41.570 --> 01:17:46.250 align:middle line:84%
And so maybe these, in fact,
are consistent with the capital

01:17:46.250 --> 01:17:49.200 align:middle line:90%
asset pricing model pretty well.

01:17:49.200 --> 01:17:53.720 align:middle line:90%
Now, let's see.

01:17:53.720 --> 01:17:59.000 align:middle line:84%
One can plot the alpha versus
the beta across all the stocks

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:02.000 align:middle line:84%
and get this result,
which suggests

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:04.800 align:middle line:84%
that when you have
higher beta, you

01:18:04.800 --> 01:18:08.680 align:middle line:90%
may get higher alpha as well.

01:18:08.680 --> 01:18:12.800 align:middle line:84%
And when you have very low
beta, maybe the low beta

01:18:12.800 --> 01:18:18.640 align:middle line:84%
is partly due to a
lower alpha potential.

01:18:18.640 --> 01:18:26.400 align:middle line:84%
But this chart doesn't show
how alpha varies by sector.

01:18:26.400 --> 01:18:31.640 align:middle line:84%
And so if we try to
look at alpha by sector

01:18:31.640 --> 01:18:36.360 align:middle line:84%
we get different fits
for different sectors,

01:18:36.360 --> 01:18:40.540 align:middle line:84%
which is too complex, really,
to interpret as graphed here.

01:18:40.540 --> 01:18:43.440 align:middle line:84%
But it serves as a
first step at trying

01:18:43.440 --> 01:18:48.090 align:middle line:84%
to understand how alphas might
vary within different sectors.

01:18:48.090 --> 01:18:51.560 align:middle line:90%


01:18:51.560 --> 01:18:59.360 align:middle line:84%
Perhaps interestingly, here's
the beta coefficient by sector.

01:18:59.360 --> 01:19:03.020 align:middle line:84%
And here, one can see
that certain sectors,

01:19:03.020 --> 01:19:10.280 align:middle line:84%
like consumer staples, have
much lower beta values.

01:19:10.280 --> 01:19:14.040 align:middle line:84%
And other sectors, like
computer and technology,

01:19:14.040 --> 01:19:16.040 align:middle line:90%
have very high betas.

01:19:16.040 --> 01:19:18.920 align:middle line:84%
So in terms of identifying
those sectors that

01:19:18.920 --> 01:19:23.060 align:middle line:84%
will have low market
risk or high market risk,

01:19:23.060 --> 01:19:28.920 align:middle line:84%
these properties
play out quite well.

01:19:28.920 --> 01:19:31.160 align:middle line:90%
And let's see.

01:19:31.160 --> 01:19:38.480 align:middle line:84%
In terms of looking at the
top and bottom stocks by beta,

01:19:38.480 --> 01:19:41.240 align:middle line:84%
well, we have consumer
discretionary, computer

01:19:41.240 --> 01:19:48.560 align:middle line:84%
technology sector stocks are
the sectors where the top 10

01:19:48.560 --> 01:19:49.620 align:middle line:90%
betas are.

01:19:49.620 --> 01:19:54.840 align:middle line:84%
And if we look at the lowest
betas, ranging from 0.37 down

01:19:54.840 --> 01:19:58.430 align:middle line:84%
to 0.18, most of these
are in consumer staples.

01:19:58.430 --> 01:20:01.680 align:middle line:90%


01:20:01.680 --> 01:20:06.000 align:middle line:84%
Finally, if we look
at the top 10 stocks

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:09.760 align:middle line:84%
with significant
alphas, OK, here

01:20:09.760 --> 01:20:14.480 align:middle line:84%
is the table of alpha
values that were highest,

01:20:14.480 --> 01:20:21.080 align:middle line:84%
and one was in oils
and energy sector ENPH,

01:20:21.080 --> 01:20:27.300 align:middle line:90%
with the alpha value of 0.003.

01:20:27.300 --> 01:20:27.800 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

01:20:27.800 --> 01:20:38.860 align:middle line:84%
Here's-- so if we have an alpha
value of 0.003, it's actually--

01:20:38.860 --> 01:20:42.440 align:middle line:90%
yeah, so 3-- whatever.

01:20:42.440 --> 01:20:43.940 align:middle line:90%
I won't have the extra.

01:20:43.940 --> 01:20:46.010 align:middle line:90%
But this is a daily alpha.

01:20:46.010 --> 01:20:52.400 align:middle line:90%


01:20:52.400 --> 01:20:59.940 align:middle line:84%
If we wanted to annualize this
daily alpha, what would that--

01:20:59.940 --> 01:21:02.730 align:middle line:84%
how would we compute
that annualized alpha?

01:21:02.730 --> 01:21:10.600 align:middle line:90%


01:21:10.600 --> 01:21:14.840 align:middle line:84%
If you're earning
this alpha every day,

01:21:14.840 --> 01:21:17.280 align:middle line:84%
it sort of is an
increment of return

01:21:17.280 --> 01:21:22.360 align:middle line:84%
that you're expecting
to get every day.

01:21:22.360 --> 01:21:30.000 align:middle line:84%
And so if we have 1 plus alpha
hat to the number of days--

01:21:30.000 --> 01:21:35.000 align:middle line:84%
there's roughly
252 days per year--

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:42.040 align:middle line:84%
and then subtract 1,
then we end up getting--

01:21:42.040 --> 01:21:44.560 align:middle line:90%
let's see.

01:21:44.560 --> 01:21:45.780 align:middle line:90%
I computed this.

01:21:45.780 --> 01:21:47.640 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:21:47.640 --> 01:21:52.860 align:middle line:84%
PETER KEMPTHORNE: It's
2.12 minus 1, basically.

01:21:52.860 --> 01:21:55.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is, like,
a hundred percent.

01:21:55.000 --> 01:21:58.120 align:middle line:84%
So this stock happened
to just deliver

01:21:58.120 --> 01:22:01.560 align:middle line:90%
a huge amount of returns.

01:22:01.560 --> 01:22:03.780 align:middle line:84%
But what's interesting
to see, though,

01:22:03.780 --> 01:22:07.520 align:middle line:84%
is that this relatively simple
model, the capital asset pricing

01:22:07.520 --> 01:22:11.240 align:middle line:84%
model, appears to be
consistent with the stocks

01:22:11.240 --> 01:22:13.360 align:middle line:90%
over a long period of time.

01:22:13.360 --> 01:22:20.240 align:middle line:84%
That being said, the more
complex models are warranted.

01:22:20.240 --> 01:22:26.560 align:middle line:84%
And the data collection
phase of this, our project,

01:22:26.560 --> 01:22:30.680 align:middle line:84%
included importing
Fama-French factors that

01:22:30.680 --> 01:22:33.680 align:middle line:84%
are extensions of sort
of the market risk

01:22:33.680 --> 01:22:37.010 align:middle line:84%
that can be used in
these models, so.

01:22:37.010 --> 01:22:43.000 align:middle line:90%